Ralph Lauren would benefit from change, experts say. Mr. Lauren‚Äôs most recent show at New York Fashion Week was an ode to Americans in Biarritz, with his signature perfect leather tailoring, blue and white evening gowns, and stars in the front row (Jessica Chastain, Julianne Moore). But his brand has a typical luxury pyramid structure, the model for both Calvin Klein and Michael Kors, with luxury at the pinnacle casting an aspirational halo over the more accessible Polo Ralph Lauren line. Factory stores below that form the bulk of the profits.Given Mr. Larsson‚Äôs track record in ‚Äúfast fashion,‚Äù the question is whether the company will now take a different tack. Recent moves at the company, like separating out its luxury business, hiring the luxury executive Valerie Hermann and opening a lavish private members‚Äô club in Milan, had suggested a stronger focus on luxury at the apparel company.Mr. Larsson has made his name in budget-conscious mass-retailing, first at H&M and then at Old Navy. Though even at those mass brands, Mr. Larsson‚Äôs success, experts say, has been built on fostering a level of attention to design that sellers of low-end, family-oriented apparel had previously not put into their wares.
Photo






Mr. Lauren‚Äôs Spring 2001 collection. His early success was built on ¬†a country-club, preppy look, and he later designed clothing based on Wild West themes.

Credit
            Corina Lecca for The New York Times        


Whether or not changes lie ahead for the company, it is a big moment for a fashion house that Mr. Lauren began in the streets of New York, selling ties out of rented drawer space in a closet of an office in the Empire State Building. Now, on top of its men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs clothing lines, Ralph Lauren has a foothold, through licensing, in everything from cosmetics to leather goods, to footwear and eyeglass frames. The company logged sales of $7.6 billion in its last fiscal year.Mr. Lauren‚Äôs success has made him a rich man. Though he remains a top shareholder, Mr. Lauren has sold off parts of his stake over the years. Just last week, he sold 50,000 Ralph Lauren shares, according to a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, worth some $5.6 million.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Susman of Threadstone said that Ralph Lauren clearly wanted to incorporate some elements of fast fashion, given Mr. Larsson‚Äôs success in that arena. Mr. Larsson will also help Ralph Lauren bolster its international presence, which has become critical as the United States market has become saturated, Mr. Susman said.But he said that he did not expect Ralph Lauren to step away from building up the luxury side of the business.‚ÄúI don‚Äôt envision that would change,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúAnd they still have Ralph Lauren to handle it.‚ÄùMr. Lauren spoke of the unlikely match between his world of aspirational luxury, and that of Mr. Larsson‚Äôs, in mass retailing. A Ralph Lauren board member had spoken gushingly about a rising star in fashion, and recommended Mr. Lauren meet him.‚ÄúSo I said, ‚ÄòWhere‚Äôs he from?‚Äô And they told me: ‚ÄòOld Navy and H&M.‚Äô I said: ‚ÄòWhy would I be looking for that? We‚Äôre building a great luxury company.‚Äô ‚ÄùEven as the two met for a private dinner in New York, Mr. Lauren said, ‚ÄúI was thinking to myself: ‚ÄòWhy am I here? It‚Äôs a waste of time.‚Äô ‚ÄùThat feeling of initial unease was mutual, Mr. Larsson said. ‚ÄúI was hesitating. Why was he interested in speaking with me?‚Äù Mr. Larsson said.But the two hit it off.‚ÄúI interviewed lots of people who were in luxury. But Stefan has a great quality that made me say: ‚ÄòYou can be my new C.E.O.,‚Äô ‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs unique as a man, a man who‚Äôs capable of building businesses and growing companies, but at the same time he‚Äôs sensitive to people‚Äôs feelings.‚ÄùAnd was there really something that Ralph Lauren could learn from H&M or Old Navy?‚ÄúIf I thought there was nothing I could learn from Stefan,‚Äù Mr. Lauren said, ‚Äúhe would not be here.‚Äù
Continue reading the main story






